"'''Never Let Me Go'''" is a song by English [[indie rock]] band [[Florence and the Machine]] from their second studio album ''[[Ceremonials]]''. The song was written by [[Florence Welch]] and [[Paul Epworth]] while production was handled by Epworth. [[Island Records]] have released the song as the fourth single from the album on 2 April 2012. The band first premiered the song during one of their concerts before the release of the album on 15 October 2011. A [[Clams Casino (musician)|Clams Casino]] remix of the song was placed on the [[12-inch single|12" white vinyl single]] which was available for pre-order on 22 March 2012.

Musically, "Never Let Me Go" is a downtempo [[baroque pop]] and [[indie pop]] ballad completed with [[piano]] and [[drum kit|drums]] while backing vocals repeatedly sing "never let me go" throughout the song. Many critics noted similarities between the song's composition and materials by other artists including [[Enya]], [[Evanescence]] and [[Ryan Tedder]]-produced songs. The song received mostly positive reviews by critics who praised Welch's vocals and its balladry nature.

An accompanying [[music video]] for the song was released online on 7 March 2012. It was directed by [[Queens of Noize|Tabitha Denholm]] and stars actor [[Jamie Campbell Bower]], who plays Welch's love interest. The video features the pair together skating and shots of a dirty water trickling down Welch's face and hands are shown. Upon the release of the video, critics praised Welch's gothic look and the video's dark atmosphere. Florence and the Machine added the song to the [[set list]] of their second worldwide [[Ceremonials Tour]] (2011<U+2013>2012) where the song was performed during the encore of the concerts along with "[[No Light, No Light]]".

==Background and release==
The song was written by [[Florence Welch]], [[Paul Epworth]] and [[Kid Harpoon]] while production was handled by Epworth.<ref name="liner">{{Cite music release notes | Name=[[Ceremonials (album)|Ceremonials]] | Type=album | Artist=[[Florence and the Machine]] | Year=2011 | Format=liner notes | Publisher=[[Island Records]]}}</ref><ref name="mv">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a369827/florence--the-machine-release-never-let-me-go-music-video-watch.html|title=Florence + the Machine release 'Never Let Me Go' music video - watch|publisher=Digital Spy. Hachette Filipacchi M<U+00E9>dias|first=Lewis|last=Corner|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref> [[Florence and the Machine]] premiered "Never Let Me Go" along with tho other songs from the album, "Spectrum" and "Heartlines" as part of their [[set list]] at New York's Creators Project on 15 October 2011, two weeks before the release of the album.<ref>Sources talking about the premiere of "Never Let Me Go", "Spectrum" and "Heartlines" on 15 October 2011 during the band's [[set list]] at New York's Creators Project before the release of ''Ceremonials'':
*{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/florence-and-the-machine/59836|title=Watch Florence And The Machine perform three new tracks from 'Ceremonials' - video|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|date=16 October 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a345974/florence--the-machine-perform-three-new-tracks-live-video.html|title=Florence + the Machine perform three new tracks live - video|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]. [[Hachette Filipacchi M<U+00E9>dias]]|first=Robert|last=Copsey|date=17 October 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2011/10/watch-florence-the-machine-debut-3-new-songs-at-cr.html|title=Watch Florence and the Machine Debut Three New Songs at Creator's Project|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|publisher=[[Wolfgang's Vault]]|first=K.|last=Alexander Smith|date=17 October 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}
*{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/10/18/showbiz/creators-project-art-music-tech/|title=Creators Project brings together art, music and tech|publisher=[[CNN]]|first=Abbey|last=Goodman|date=18 October 2011|accessdate=8 March 2012}}
</ref> Speaking about the song, Welch told [[Digital Spy]], "The gospel thing comes from my obsession with hymns. I'm drawn to anything that has a hymnal quality, be it Spiritualized or dusty old albums by Georgian choirs."<ref name="release">{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Robert|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a368811/florence--the-machine-announce-new-single-never-let-me-go.html|title=Florence + the Machine announce new single 'Never Let Me Go'|publisher=Digital Spy. Hachette Filipacchi M<U+00E9>dias|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref> [[Island Records]] will release "Never Let Me Go" as the fourth single from the album on 2 April 2012.<ref name="release" /> A [[Clams Casino (musician)|Clams Casino]] remix of the song was placed on the [[12-inch single|12" white vinyl single]] which was available for pre-order on 22 March 2012.<ref name="vinyl">{{cite web|url=http://florenceandthemachine.net/news/0-6/pre-order-never-let-me-go/0-6|title=Pre-Oorded 'Never Let Me Go'|publisher=Florence and the Machine's official website|date=22 March 2012|accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> The artwork for the vinyl single was shot by [[Karl Lagerfeld]] and was described by ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Michael Cragg as "swanky".<ref name="swanky" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/13326-never-let-me-go-clams-casino-remix/?utm_medium=site&utm_source=related-content&utm_name=tracks|title=Florence and the Machine - "Never Let Me Go (Clams Casino Remix)"|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|first=Larry|last=Fitzmaurice|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> Andrew Martin of ''Prefix Magazine'' commented that the "Clams Casino's remix of [the song]... was the weirdest thing to happen to Florence Welch's voice".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prefixmag.com/news/florence-welch-planning-strange-album-with-dev-hyn/63528/|title=Florence Welch Planning "Strange Album" With Dev Hynes?|work=Prefix Magazine|first=Andrew|last=Martin|date=22 March 2012|accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Michael Cragg commented, "He takes the stately Never Let Me Go and adds gusts of distorted backing vocals, big drum claps and, midway through, pitches Florence Welch's vocals down a notch or two to create what sounds like an eerie duet recorded in a cave."<ref name="swanky">{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/musicblog/2012/mar/22/new-music-florence-machine-never-let-remix|title=New music: Florence & the Machine <U+2013> Never Let Me Go (Clams Casino Remix)|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|first=Michael|last=Cragg|date=22 March 2012|accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>

==Composition==
"Never Let Me Go" is a downtempo [[baroque pop]] and [[indie pop]] ballad with elements of [[Soul music|soul]], [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[pop music]].<ref name="priyaelan" /><ref name="trackbytrack" /> It has a [[piano]]-led instrumentation accompanied by thumping [[Drum kit|drums]].<ref name="guardian.co.uk" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/reviews/florence-and-the-machine-ceremonials|title=Florence And The Machine - Ceremonials|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|first=Laura|last=Foster|date=24 October 2011|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref> Lyrically, the theme of the song revolves around the [[sea]] and the [[ocean]], interpreted in the lines "The arms of the ocean so sweet and so cold/And all this devotion I never knew at all".<ref name="priyaelan" /><ref name="phoenix" /> The song also talks about [[sin]] and [[Redemption (theology)|redemption]].<ref name="HitFix" /> The opening lyrics "Looking out from underneath, fractured moonlight on the sea",<ref name="spyrev" /> of the song sound similar to the songs written by [[Elizabeth Fraser]] in the group [[This Mortal Coil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2011/oct/27/florence-and-the-machine-ceremonials-review|title=Florence and the Machine: Ceremonials <U+2013> review (Island)|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|first=Michael|last=Hann|date=27 October 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref> Backing vocals are heard during the chorus repeatedly singing the lines "never let me go".<ref name="priyaelan">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=140&title=first_listen_florence_aamp_the_machine_c&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|title=First Listen - Florence & The Machine, 'Ceremonials'|work=NME|publisher=IPC Media|first=Priya|last=Elan|date=13 September 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref> Many critics noted similarities between "Never Let Me Go" and artists such as [[Enya]] and [[Evanescence]].<ref name="priyaelan" /><ref name="dspy">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/thesound/a340576/florence--the-machines-new-album-ceremonials-first-listen.html|title=Florence + the Machine's new album 'Ceremonials' - First listen|publisher=Digital Spy. Hachette Filipacchi M<U+00E9>dias|first=Robert|last=Copsey|date=15 September 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2011/oct/30/florence-machine-ceremonials-review|title=Florence and the Machine: Ceremonials <U+2013> review (Island)|work=[[The Observer]]|publisher=Guardian Media Group|first=Kitty|last=Empire|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref> The production of the song was also compared with [[Ryan Tedder]]-produced songs like [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]]' "[[Halo (Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles song)|Halo]]" (2009) [[Jordin Sparks]]' "[[Battlefield (song)|Battlefield]]" (2009), [[Kelly Clarkson]]'s "[[Already Gone (Kelly Clarkson song)|Already Gone]]" (2009) and [[Leona Lewis]]' "[[Bleeding Love]]" (2007).<ref name="guardian.co.uk" /> Jillian Mapes of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine further noted that "Never Let Me Go" sounds more similar to the songs from the band's debut studio album ''[[Lungs (album)|Lungs]]'' (2009).<ref name="trackbytrack">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/features/florence-the-machine-ceremonials-track-by-1005465362.story|title=Florence + The Machine, 'Ceremonials': Track-By-Track Review|first=Jillian|last=Mapes|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=2 November 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref>

==Critical reception==
While reviewing ''Ceremonials'', Neil McCormick of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' chose "Never Let Me Go" as a highlight on the whole album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/cdreviews/8853291/Florence-and-the-Machine-Ceremonials-CD-review.html|title=Florence & the Machine: Ceremonials, CD review|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|first=Neil|last=McCormick|date=27 October 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref> Rebecca Nicholson of ''The Guardian'' praised the song saying that it has "thumping stadium drums and sounds like it has the US charts in its epic crosshairs."<ref name="guardian.co.uk">{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/musicblog/2011/sep/15/florence-machine-ceremonials|title=First listen: Florence and the Machine's new album, Ceremonials|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|first=Rebecca|last=Nicholson|date=15 September 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref> Similarly, Robert Copsey of Digital Spy said, "Big enough to bring a stadium audience to its knees, it's more structured and less hectic than anything on her debut, but still remains packed with eccentricities."<ref name="dspy" /> In a separate review of the single, Copsey graded it with four out of five stars saying, "she chants with pent-up emotion over a neo-gothic piano riff, before letting it all pour out on a chorus of sweeping strings and crashing cymbals. The result is her least hectic cut to date, but much like her contemporaries, remains full of eccentricity."<ref name="spyrev">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a373207/florence--the-machine-never-let-me-go-single-review.html|title=Florence + the Machine: 'Never Let Me Go' - Single review|publisher=Digital Spy. Hachette Filipacchi M<U+00E9>dias|first=Robert|last=Copsey|date=March 26, 2012|accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> [[Slant Magazine]]{{'}}s Matthew Cole called the song "gorgeous... [and] easily the best ballad Florence has done yet".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/florence-and-the-machine-ceremonials/2666|title=Florence and the Machine: Ceremonials|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|first=Matthew|last=Cole|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref> Another writer of the same publication commented that "Welch is perfectly capable of doing delicate too, as evidenced by... "Never Let Me Go".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/the-25-best-albums-of-2011/294|title=The 25 Best Albums of 2011|publisher=Slant Magazine|page=1|date=14 December 2011|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref> David Edwards of the website [[Drowned in Sound]] commented that "by the end of the superb 'Never Let Me Go', you could easily be forgiven for thinking that you are listening to one of the most unexpected surprises of 2011, so strong and resonant is the roar of the opening salvo."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16620/reviews/4143919|title=Florence + The Machine - Ceremonials|publisher=[[Drowned in Sound]]|first=David|last=Edwards|date=31 October 2011|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref> Richard Smirke of ''Billboard'' magazine called the song an "impassioned midpaced ballad".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/features/florence-the-machine-the-billboard-cover-1005379192.story?page=2|title=Florence & The Machine: The Billboard Cover Story|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|page=2|first=Richard|last=Smirke|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> Ryan Reed of ''[[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Phoenix]]'' gave a mixed review for the song saying "When she exclaims, 'It's all over; I'm going under,' it's unclear whether she's committing suicide or practicing her can-opener dive. Either way, it's boring. On occasion, her show-off-y melisma floats past acquired taste into plain ol' ridiculousness.<ref name="phoenix">{{cite web|url=http://thephoenix.com/Boston/music/129186-florence-the-machine-ceremonials/|title=Florence + the Machine - Ceremonials|work=[[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Phoenix]]|publisher=[[Phoenix Media/Communications Group]]|first=Ryan|last=Reed|date=3 November 2011|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref>

==Music video==
{{quote box|width=29%|quote="Of course, given the cavernous, darkly lit spaces the video inhabits, it's also a nice fit to the song's voluminous, dream-like sonics. Truly, a skating rink hasn't looked this moody since, well, ever <U+2014> to the point where you can practically feel the chill running its way up Welch's stockings. And as for Campbell Bower, well, he's plenty icy too... Call it love on ice. Or a darkly spiritual rumination on the politics of figure skating. Either way, with 'Never Let Me Go,' Welch definitely adds to her impressive list of eye-catching clips, emotes and wails and flails, and gives skating its biggest artistic bump... It's chillingly effective, and just as beautiful, too."| source= -James Montgomery, MTV News<ref name="mtv1680674" />}}

An accompanying music video for the song was released on [[Bing]] on 7 March 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://florenceandthemachine.net/news/0-6/watch-the-never-let-me-go-video/0-6/|title=Watch The 'Never Let Me Go' Video|publisher=Florence and the Machine's official website|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> A picture of Welch swimming in the music video for the song was shown on ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' on 1 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/music/article4164215.ece|title=Way to go, Flo|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|publisher=[[News International]]|first=Gordon|last=Smart|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref> Along with the music video, behind-the-scenes video was also released. It was directed by [[Queens of Noize|Tabitha Denholm]].<ref name="doseca" /><ref name="mtv1680674" /> The video stars actor [[Jamie Campbell Bower]] who plays Welch's love interest in the video.<ref name="cos" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/florence-and-the-machine/62510|title=Watch Florence Welch melt to death alongside 'Twilight' star in 'Never Let Me Go' video|work=NME|publisher=IPC Media|date=8 March 2012|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>

The video starts with Welch looking into an ice rink which holds an arcade. A man is seen using the arcade machines as Welch enters, wearing torn, worn away clothing. As the first chorus starts, the ice rink is lit up by the man with spotlights moving around. Several scenes are shown throughout the video of water e.g. an overflowing sink, a floor being mopped, watery footprints on the floor. What looks like dirty water is shown trickling down Welch's face and hands. She walks onto the ice rink and the man enters, leading them to dance with each other and hug. As Florence dances on her own, a cleaner is shown to be watching. Towards the end of the song, Welch looks at the man and starts to fall back, her face and hands engulfed by dirty water as the woman cleaner looks on.

Nick Neyland of ''Prefix Magazine'' compared the video with [[Kazuo Ishiguro]]'s eponymous novel, ''[[Never Let Me Go (novel)|Never Let Me Go]]'' (2005).<ref name="pmag">{{cite web|url=http://www.prefixmag.com/media/florence-the-machine/never-let-me-go-video/62857/|title=Florence + The Machine: "Never Let Me Go" (Video)|work=Prefix Magazine|first=Nick|last=Neyland|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref> Melinda Newman of the website [[HitFix]] praised Welch's [[Gothic (term)|gothic]] look and wrote, "It's spooky and we don't fully understand it. It<U+2019>s one of those videos that creates an atmosphere more than a linear story."<ref name="HitFix">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/the-beat-goes-on/posts/watch-florence-the-machine-go-goth-in-new-video-for-never-let-me-go|title=Watch: Florence + The Machine go goth in new video for 'Never Let Me Go'|publisher=[[HitFix]]|first=Melinda|last=Newman|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> Leah Collins of the Canadian magazine ''[[Dose (magazine)|Dose]]'' commented that in the video, "Welch is the sort of gal who busts into skating rinks after hours with her skid boyfriend... The kind of gal who dyes her hair by summoning dark, demonic spirits -- ones who ooze out of her pores, and various plumbing fixtures, until she's nothing but a black-haired creepy mist."<ref name="doseca">{{cite web|url=http://www.dose.ca/music/Florence+Machine+Creep+Twilight+Actor+Video+Never/6266342/story.html?cid=dose_nav_drop|title=Florence + The Machine Out-Creep Twilight Actor in New Video "Never Let Me Go"|work=[[Dose (magazine)|Dose]]|publisher=[[Postmedia Network]]|first=Leah|last=Collins|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> [[MTV News]]' James Montgomery called the video "ethereal" and said, "Never Let Me Go" is certainly visually arresting, but it also works on another level: Namely, it perfectly (and artfully) captures the experience of literally melting in the presence of a lover, the feeling of casting abandon to the wind and giving yourself away truly and completely."<ref name="mtv1680674">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1680674/florence-machine-jamie-campbell-bower-never-let-me-go-video.jhtml|title='Twilight' Star Gets Eerie In Florence And The Machine Video|publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[MTV Networks]]|first=James|last=Montgomery|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> Ayeesha Walsh of ''The Sun'' praised the "spooky" clip adding, "The dark and meaningful imaging is a powerful combination with the enchanting soundtrack of single Never Let Me Go and it's a captivating performance from Florence."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/music/4181032/Florence-Welch-vamps-it-up-for-new-video.html|title=Florence Welch vamps it up for new video|work=The Sun|publisher=News International|first=Ayeesha|last=Walsh|date=8 March 2012|accessdate=9 March 2012}}</ref> [[Consequence of Sound]]'s Alex Young commented briefly "Don<U+2019>t watch this one before breakfast."<ref name="cos">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/03/video-florence-and-the-machine-never-let-me-go/|title=Video: Florence and the Machine <U+2013> <U+201C>Never Let Me Go<U+201D>|publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]]. Complex Media Network|first=Alex|last=Young|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref> A writer of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' gave a mixed review for the video, saying that it had an unclear plot<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/08/florence-and-the-machine-never-let-me-go_n_1327784.html|title=Florence And The Machine's 'Never Let Me Go' Gets A Video|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=8 March 2012|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>

==Live performances==
Florence and the Machine added the song to the set list of their second worldwide [[Ceremonials Tour]] (2011<U+2013>2012) where the song was performed during the encore of the concerts along with "[[No Light, No Light]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-12-05/news/chi-florence-and-the-machine-concert-review-florence-welch-at-the-chicago-theatre-reviewed-20111204_1_florence-welch-rabbit-heart-chicago-theatre|title=There's more to Florence Welch than wispiness and eccentricity|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=Tribune Company|first=Greg|last=Kot|authorlink=Greg Kot|date=5 December 2011|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/music/4171420/Caught-Live-Florence-And-The-Machine-O2-Dublin.html|title=Caught Live: Florence And The Machine @ O2, Dublin|work=The Sun|publisher=News International|first=Gordon|last=Smart|date=4 March 2012|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>

